                <h2><u>Drug Dosage Based on Body Weight</u></h2>
                <p>Drug dose for certain drugs is based on the weight of the patient. 
                The dose is expressed as the quantity of drug per unit of patient weight such as 
                <i>milligrams of drug per kilogram of body weight or mg/kg. </i>
                A useful equation for calculating drug dosage based on body weight is:
                </p>
                <div class="formulae"><p>  $$ { Patient's \ Dose \ (mg)  =  Patient's \ Weight (kg) \times } {  Drug \ dose \ (mg) \over 1 \ (kg)} $$</p></div>
                
                <p>Although mg/kg is a commonly used unit for expressing drug concentration, 
                other units such as &mu;g/kg are also used. In addition, patient’s weight is reported in pounds. 
                The above equation may be used for different units as long as the terms used are consistently applied.</p>
                
