                    </table>
                    
                    
                    <p>The above examples, took into consideration patients <i>actual body weight (ABW)</i> to calculate drug dose for the patient. 
                    However, many medications do not distribute well into fat because they are hydrophilic, if an obese patient is given a dose based on ABW, it would result in an overdose. Such medication are dosed on the patients 
                    <i>ideal body weight (IBW)</i> which is defined as the weight of a patient’s lean body mass.
                    Following equations are used for calculating IBW for males and females:</p>
                    
                    <div class="formulae"> $$ Male: {50 \ kg + (2.3 \ kg)(each \ inch \ > \ 5 \ ft) } = IBW \ in \ kilograms $$</div>
                    <div class="formulae"> $$ Female: {45.5 \ kg + (2.3 \ kg)(each \ inch \ > \ 5 \ ft) } = IBW \ in \ kilograms $$</div>
